## Branching strategy

Two long-lived branches:

- **`main`** is the release branch. Release-please watches only `main`, so a tag and Release happen exactly when something lands here. `main` should always be deployable.
- **`dev`** is the integration branch. Feature and fix PRs target `dev`. CI runs cheap checks (unit + integration) on every PR there.

Periodically — when `dev` has accumulated a release window's worth of work — open a `dev → main` promotion PR. Merging it triggers release-please.

### Why squash-merge is disabled

Release-please reads Conventional Commits subjects on `main` to compute the next version bump. Squash-merge collapses N commits into one whose subject becomes the PR title — so a `dev → main` PR titled `chore: promote dev to main` would hide every `feat:` and `fix:` underneath, and release-please would bump nothing.

The repo allows only **merge-commit** and **rebase-and-merge**. Both preserve individual commit subjects on `main`, so release-please sees them all and computes the highest applicable bump (`feat!` > `feat:` > `fix:` > nothing). Click whichever button GitHub offers; both are correct.

### Bump arithmetic across a batch

Release-please computes one bump per release window, not one per commit. Across the commits in a `dev → main` promotion:

- Any `feat!:` or `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer → major (`X.0.0`)
- Any `feat:` (no breaking) → minor (`x.Y.0`)
- Only `fix:` / `perf:` → patch (`x.y.Z`)
- All `chore:` / `docs:` / `refactor:` / `test:` / `ci:` / `style:` → no bump, no release PR

Three fixes plus two features in one promotion produces one minor bump, not five releases.

