## Release process

Two automation layers:

1. **`.github/workflows/release-please.yml`** maintains a "chore: release vX.Y.Z" PR that accumulates pending changes. Each commit to `main` updates the open release PR (or opens a new one) with the next version computed from Conventional Commits-style commit subjects (`feat:` → minor bump, `fix:` → patch, `BREAKING CHANGE:` in body → major). The release PR contains the version bump in `core/pyproject.toml` + `.release-please-manifest.json`. **Release-please does not touch `CHANGELOG.md`** — see "CHANGELOG handling" below.
2. **`.github/workflows/release.yml`** triggers when a `vX.Y.Z` tag is pushed. Matrix-builds all 5 variants for `linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`, publishes `ghcr.io/baelfur/{{ app_name }}-{variant}:X.Y.Z` (and updates `:latest` for stable versions), then creates a GitHub Release whose body is the matching `CHANGELOG.md` section.

### Maintainer flow

1. Open a feature/fix PR against `dev` with a Conventional Commits-style title (`feat: ...`, `fix: ...`, `docs: ...`, `chore: ...`). For breaking changes include `BREAKING CHANGE:` in the commit body.
2. Add an entry under `## [Unreleased]` in `CHANGELOG.md` describing the change in the project's hand-curated voice.
3. Merge the PR. CI runs unit + integration on `dev`.
4. Repeat for additional features/fixes; they all accumulate on `dev`.
5. When ready to release, open a `dev → main` PR. **`validate-build.yml` runs the full 5-variant matrix as a required check** — the merge button stays disabled until every variant builds cleanly. Once green, merge it (any non-squash button — squash is disabled).
6. Release-please opens or updates the standing release PR with the computed version bump. **`build-smoke.yml` runs as a required check on the release PR** — single-variant smoke gate to catch any regression between dev → main merge and tag creation.
7. Merge the release PR. Release-please pushes the tag, which triggers the GHCR build + GitHub Release. `release.yml` reads the `[Unreleased]` block from `CHANGELOG.md` as the Release body, then a bot follow-up commit closes `[Unreleased]` to `[X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD` and starts a fresh empty `[Unreleased]` for the next cycle.

The build gates at steps 5 and 6 mean the tag is the last thing that happens. If either gate fails, the PR doesn't merge, the version doesn't increment, no tag is created — fix-forward isn't necessary because nothing was committed.

Breaking changes require a prominent note in the release CHANGELOG section with migration guidance.

### CHANGELOG handling

The CHANGELOG is hand-curated for narrative quality (themed sub-sections, contextual justifications, cross-references between related entries). Release-please's auto-generated CHANGELOG would be plainer (`### Features` / `### Bug Fixes` from raw commit subjects). To keep editorial control while still benefiting from release-please's tag automation, `release-please-config.json` sets `skip-changelog: true` per package — release-please bumps the version and creates the tag but never modifies `CHANGELOG.md`.

### Pre-releases

Pre-release tags (`vX.Y.Z-rc.1`, `vX.Y.Z-beta.2`) follow the same flow but are flagged as pre-release on GitHub and do **not** update the `:latest` Docker tag — operators pin pre-releases explicitly.

## Reverting

Each release is a git tag on `main`. To roll back a running deployment, pin your Docker image to the previous version tag (e.g. `ghcr.io/baelfur/app-postgres:X.Y.Z-1` instead of `:X.Y.Z`) and redeploy. {{ display_name }} is a stateless read layer — no migrations to unwind.
